  <h2>Where I Buy Houses in Wichita</h2>
  <p>I'm active all across the Wichita metro. I've bought in east Wichita, west Wichita, north and south — as well as surrounding communities including Derby, Andover, Haysville, Mulvane, Valley Center, El Dorado, and Augusta. If you're within a reasonable drive of Wichita and need to sell, call me and we'll figure out if it makes sense.</p>
  <p>I'm not chasing a specific neighborhood profile. I look at the property and the situation — not just the zip code.</p>

  <h2>Why "We Buy Houses" Companies Exist — And What to Watch For</h2>
  <p>The "we buy houses" market in Wichita has grown a lot in the last few years. That's mostly good for sellers — more buyers means more competition, and more competition usually means better offers. But not every cash buyer operates the same way.</p>
  <p>Some things to pay attention to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Proof of funds.</strong> A legitimate cash buyer can show you they have the money to close. If someone's making offers without being able to demonstrate that, ask questions.</li>
    <li><strong>Transparent offer math.</strong> I'll show you how I got to my number — what the comparable sales look like, what I'm factoring in for repairs. If a buyer won't explain their offer, that's worth noting.</li>
    <li><strong>No-pressure timeline.</strong> You should never feel rushed into accepting an offer. A good buyer gives you time to decide and doesn't create fake urgency.</li>
    <li><strong>Local knowledge.</strong> Someone who actually knows Wichita — the neighborhoods, the market, the title companies — closes deals more smoothly than someone operating from out of state.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>I can only speak for how I operate. But those are the questions worth asking anyone you're considering selling to.</p>

  <h2>What Kinds of Houses I Buy</h2>
  <p>The short answer is most of them. The longer answer:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Houses that need significant repairs or updates</li>
    <li>Inherited properties — whether probate is complete or still in process</li>
    <li>Properties with title issues, liens, or code violations</li>
    <li>Homes with tenants in place</li>
    <li>Vacant homes that have been sitting</li>
    <li>Properties going through foreclosure</li>
    <li>Homes in any stage of a divorce settlement</li>
    <li>Fire, water, or storm damaged properties</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If your situation isn't on that list, call anyway. The worst I can say is it doesn't work for me, and I'll tell you that honestly rather than waste your time.</p>

